        "excerpt": "The message was true and one of great conflict, but he understood the message and had an understanding of the vision.",
        "body": "Verse 1 is unique in the book of Daniel — it is a third-person editorial summary inserted before the first-person narrative begins in verse 2. This is not accidental. The narrator steps outside the story to certify three things before the reader enters it: (1) the message was true (emet — reliable, fixed, faithfully corresponding to reality); (2) it concerned great conflict (tsava — often translated 'warfare' or 'great army,' the same word used for the host of heaven and the military service of the Levites in Numbers 4:23); and (3) Daniel understood it. The editorial frame functions as a hermeneutical lens: what follows is not confused prophecy or ambiguous symbolism — it is a true message about real cosmic warfare, and it was comprehended.\n\nThe significance of tsava ('great conflict') at the outset is that it prepares the reader for what will be disclosed in verses 13 and 20 — the prince of Persia, the prince of Greece, the cosmic resistance to the heavenly messenger. The battle is not merely metaphorical. The editorial note says this before Daniel describes his fast, before the vision appears, before the messenger explains anything. The reader is meant to enter the chapter already knowing: what is behind the curtain is war.\n\nThe phrase 'and he understood' (wayyaben, from bin) placed at the end of the editorial note is also significant. Understanding of this kind of message — a message about cosmic conflict and latter-day eschatology — is a gift, not an achievement. Daniel will still prostrate himself (10:9) and still need to be touched three times before he can stand (10:10, 16, 18). Understanding does not preclude being overwhelmed; it precedes being commissioned.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Emet* (truth) appears here and again in 10:21 as 'the writing of truth' — the word bookends the chapter, asserting that what lies between the two uses of the term is reliable revelation, not speculation. *Tsava* (conflict/warfare) is the word for Israel's military campaigns (Joshua 22:12), the service of the Levites (Numbers 4:23), and the host of heaven (1 Kings 22:19) — its use here flags that 'great conflict' has cosmic, not merely geopolitical, scope."
